WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:10.280
Hi, today we're going to show you how to connect GitHub Copilot to an rstudio project on Posit

00:00:10.280 --> 00:00:11.280
Cloud.

00:00:11.280 --> 00:00:16.080
The first thing to do is create a new rstudio project, and when the project is loading,

00:00:16.080 --> 00:00:22.600
we can go ahead and give it a name, maybe AI Coding Assistant, and then as soon as the

00:00:22.600 --> 00:00:27.520
project loads, we're going to go ahead and authenticate through GitHub.

00:00:27.520 --> 00:00:34.080
To do that, you're going to click Tools on the navigation bar, then Global Options, scroll

00:00:34.080 --> 00:00:40.160
down to Copilot, and you can enable GitHub Copilot.

00:00:40.160 --> 00:00:45.279
First you're going to install some packages in the IDE, and once this is ready, you're

00:00:45.279 --> 00:00:48.439
going to be able to sign in now to GitHub.

00:00:48.439 --> 00:00:52.439
So if you click on this button, it's going to give you a verification code, you can copy

00:00:52.439 --> 00:00:56.880
that and take it to a GitHub link.

00:00:56.880 --> 00:01:03.959
Paste in the verification code, click Continue, Authorize GitHub Copilot, and now you're

00:01:03.959 --> 00:01:09.839
done here, you can close this tab, and come back into the IDE.

00:01:09.839 --> 00:01:17.559
This will update, and it'll show you that you are now logged in and ready to use Copilot.

00:01:17.559 --> 00:01:26.440
So we can open up a new script to show it off, maybe I'll rename that EDA.R, and we

00:01:26.440 --> 00:01:29.320
can start passing in, you know, human language text, right?

00:01:29.320 --> 00:01:36.480
Make a function that's going to calculate the area of a room.

00:01:36.480 --> 00:01:40.959
You can click Enter, and you're going to see the recommendation from GitHub Copilot.

00:01:40.959 --> 00:01:44.639
You can click Tab to accept the recommendation, and you can run it, and now you have a function

00:01:44.639 --> 00:01:46.959
area in your environment.

00:01:46.959 --> 00:01:52.000
You can also ask it to say, you know, I have a room of a certain size, find out the area

00:01:52.000 --> 00:01:56.440
of the floor, and it's going to know that it's going to take the formula that it just

00:01:56.440 --> 00:02:03.760
defined and be able to run this and find out that the area is in fact 80 for my size room.

00:02:03.760 --> 00:02:05.720
I can also use, like, an autocomplete.

00:02:05.720 --> 00:02:14.320
So let's load in ggplot2, and if I start typing the function ggplot here, you're going to

00:02:14.320 --> 00:02:18.320
see that it's going to start filling it in for me with some, you know, recommendations.

00:02:18.839 --> 00:02:22.960
Okay, let's just go ahead and accept this and see what it comes up with.

00:02:22.960 --> 00:02:27.919
You know, a pretty basic first ggplot, but then you can work with it again with human

00:02:27.919 --> 00:02:33.320
language and say things like, well, maybe I want to change the color of the data points.

00:02:33.320 --> 00:02:41.000
I'm going to do that based on the variable class.

00:02:41.000 --> 00:02:47.479
We can accept this and run it, and now we've got, you know, a slightly improved graphic,

00:02:47.520 --> 00:02:52.759
and you can keep iterating on this using Copilot to help you out, make new things, and hopefully

00:02:52.759 --> 00:02:53.399
make them faster.

